Team Kenya had mixed performances in the ITF Under -12 championships in Kampala, Uganda yesterday. The girls' side lost their opening tie 3-0 to Tanzania. Irene Munishi beat Seline Ahoya 6-4, 6-2 in the first singles match while Nasha Shingo trounced Stacey Chepkemoi 6-3, 6-3 for unassailable 2-0.  Munishi and Shingo then teamed up in the doubles to dispatch Chepkemoi and Taneisha Mosi 6-4, 4-6, 10-5. The boys salvaged pride for Kenya by thrashing Burundi 3-0. Zayann Virani beat Igiraneza Miki 6-1, 6-2 as Baraka Ominde overcame Hamenimana Nuru 7-5, 6-0In the doubles category, Ominde and Virani beat Jodi Gataka and Igiraneza Miki 6-2, 6-0. Head coach Joseph Karanja said there is room for improvement from both the boys and girls in the upcoming matches. "There are certain aspects of play we have to improve on going into the other matches and I believe we will get better” added Karanja. The event has attracted Uganda, Tanzania, Rwanda, Burundi, Sudan, Seychelles and Comoros among others. Elsewhere, the Karen Open tennis championship is slated for June this year. The event is expected to attract some of the country's top players.  Among the players expected include Sheil Kotecha, Ibrahim Kibet, Kevin Cheruiyot and Albert Njogu among others. The girls' category will feature the likes of top-seeded Angela Okutoyi, Sneha Kotecha and Shufaa Changawa among others. Foreign players are also expected for the week-long championship.